@node INSTALL "Installation"

PealIt!Pro requires no special installation, and may be run from any location. MUI and AHI must be obtained separately - please see their documentation for details on how to install them.

Please note that the bell images that are loaded in for the Bell Display are remapped to the colours of the current system, so you should make sure that you are running PealIt!Pro on a screen with at least 16 colours if you want them to look okay. To do this, go to the Preferences Menu, and select MUI Settings. In the window that appears, select System, and set up the program to open on a 16 (or more) colour screen.

Alternatively, if you are running PealIt!Pro on the Workbench screen, make sure that the Workbench screen has at least 16 colours.

@endnode

@node INTRO "Introduction"

PealIt!Pro is intended as an aid to bellringers, rather than a program which will teach you how to ring, though anyone learning will find this program useful.

The program's main features are as follows:
	- To convert place notations into a method (eg, from 5.1.5.etc into 123456,214356,etc).
	- Store a database of place notations which can be saved to disk.
	- Play methods. You can take control of a bell yourself to practise ringing.

There are many other features, such as being able to call bob and single lead heads (or pre-define a sequence), set the speed, introduce random variation in the speed, and more...

Program Details...
	- Written in C++.
	- Uses AHI for sound output, thus supporting sound cards, and allowing 8 channel 14 bit ouput on standard Amigas.
	- Uses MUI for interface.
	- 'Animated' bells rendered in Cinema4D!

@endnode

@node INSTR "Instructions"

The PealIt!Pro interface consists of 4 main windows, which are described below. Note that although the Play window stays open all the time, the others may be closed by clicking on the usual close gadget without quiting the program. You may reopen windows by selecting from the 'Windows' menu. To quit, choose 'Quit' from the 'Project' menu (or press right Amiga and 'Q'). The other menu items mainly duplicate what is available in the windows, so should be fairly self-explanatory when you have read this below.

The windows are as follows:

@{"b"}Place Notation Entry@{"ub"} window:

Here you can enter in the details of a place notation. You enter the name, the place notation, and the plain, bob and single lead heads. You select the number of bells to be played for with the slider bar (from 3 to 8). Note that the bob and single lead head entries may be left blank, but the other fields must be filled. For example:
	Name: Plain Bob Doubles
	Place Notation: 5.1.5.1.5.1.5.1.5
	Plain Lead Head: 125
	Bob Lead Head: 145
	Single Lead Head:
	Number of Bells: 5
(ie, the single lead head has been left blank.) Now you should click on 'Add to Place Notation Library', and the name will appear in the 'Place Notation Library' window, assuming you entered the data correctly. If not, you will be informed of the error. Clicking on 'Replace in Place Notation Library' will overwrite the place notation that is currently selected in the 'Place Notation Library' window - useful when you are editing existing place notations. You can clear the entries quickly by selecting 'Clear'.

Note that until you register, you can only use 5 bells.

@{"b"}Place Notation Library@{"ub"} window:

This is a database of place notations. You can enter/edit place notations, as well as load and save the entire library. The buttons are as follows:
	Load - Loads a library from disk, selected by a standard ASL file requester. Note that the registered version of PealIt!Pro comes with a file of over 80 5 bell methods (the file 'Notations_5bell.pi2'), which you can load in. Note that the file is merged with the existing database, that is, the library loaded in will appear any existing entries. If you don't want this to happen, select 'Delete All' first. If you have not registered, you can only load in the supplied 'Notations_LITE.pi2' file, whch has only 20 place notations.
	Save - Saves the entire database to disk. Note that any libraries you create may be freely distributed of course, and feel free to send them into me for inclusion in future releases. You can only save if you have registered.
	Convert to Method - This takes the place notation, and converts it into a method. It will appear in the 'Current Method' window, ready to be played back. You will be asked if you want to use 'All Plains' (plain lead heads all the way through), or 'Defined Sequence' (you can define a sequence of plain, bob and single lead heads to follow - see later).
	Edit - Allows you to edit the selected notation. It will appear in the 'Place Notation Entry' window. You should select 'Replace in Place Notation Library', so the original version will be replaced by the edited version.
	Delete - Deletes the selected place notation.
	Delete All - Deletes the entire library.
	Define Sequence - This allows you to define an order of plain, bob and single lead heads to be called in order when converting the place notation into a method. In the window that appears, enter a 'p', 'b' or 's' for plain, bob and single lead head respectively. Note that you can enter as many or as few entries as you like, and the method will be calculated for as long as required. Note that to use your defined sequence, you should select 'Defined Sequence' when you click on 'Convert to Method'. It is also possible to call different lead heads in real time, as you are playing back - see later for details. Note you must register for this feature.

@{"b"}Current Method@{"ub"} window:

This window simply holds the current method for you to view.

@{"b"}Playback@{"ub"} window:

Here is where you control the playing back of your methods. Note that there are two main ways to play, as chosen by the 'Play:' Cycle gadget (at the top of the window):
	Current Method - This plays whatever is shown in the 'Current Method' window, so you must first convert a method from a Place Notation as described above.
	Selected Place Notation - This plays the Place Notation which is currently selected in the 'Place Notation Library' window. The difference is that the notation is converted into a method 'on the fly', so to speak, rather than beforehand. This means you can call plain, bob and single lead heads as you are playing by selecting the buttons 'Plain', 'Bob' and 'Single'. Note that the program will continue playing in this mode until you select stop.

If you have not registered, you can only play the Current Method.

The other buttons operate as follows:
	Plain, Bob, Single - as described above.
	Control - Here you can choose to take control of a bell yourself. Use the pop-up/cycle gadget to select a bell, and this bell will not be played by the computer; you should play it yourself by selecting 'Play Bell'. This way you can practise playing. If 'No Bell' is selected, then the computer will play all the bells.
	Play Bell - Play your bell, if you are controlling a bell, as described above.
	Play - Start Playing
	Continue - If you are playing the Current Method, then this will play from the position currently highlighted in the 'Current Method' window. You cannot continue when playing from Place Notations.
	Stop - Stop playback!

Note that the playback is fully multithreaded - you can continue to use the rest of the program whilst PealIt!Pro is playing.

The 'Change Settings' opens a preferences window. 'Delay' sets the delay in 50ths of a second between each bell sounding. You can also set the 'Random variation factor'. This varies the delay randomly by the chosen amount. This is to make the playing more lifelike maybe, as not all bell ringers tend to be in perfect time... (Alternatively, set the slder to zero to turn of random variation). Select 'Use' or 'Cancel' accordingly. 'Apply' makes your changes take effect, but leaves the window open. You can only change these settings if you have registered.

@{"b"}Bell Display@{"ub"} window:

This window shows images of bells (1 is leftmost). They will 'swing' as they sound when playin back. Okay, it's poor animation, but it lets you see when each bell is sounding. The images were rendered in Cinema4D btw, but they seem to have come off a bit poor in 16 colours...

@endnode

@node CREDITS "Credits..."

Version 1 of PealIt!Pro was written way back in 1995 with the help of some friends. A Mac version was also written, but although it offered similar features, and shared the name, it was designed completely differently... The Amiga version was written in AMOSPro, and although I was pleased with it at the time, and still did a reasonable job, I thought it was time to do a lot better.

Version 2 was written in the summer of 1998, completely rewritten in C++, using MUI for the interface and AHI for better sound. It also is a lot easier to use and offers many more features.

Credits are as follows:

	Mark Harman	- Amiga Programming, Design, Amiga beta testing
	Ste Chambers	- Idea, Design, Method libraries, Amiga version 1 beta tesing
	Ben Dudman	- Sampling of Bells
	Steph Gray	- Mac Programming, Design, Mac beta testing
	Rob Forster	- Method libraries, Beta testing and other such matters

